					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/misterbibs" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(453823); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=453823&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251227" alt="MisterBibs" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=453823)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/misterbibs" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(453823); return false;" >MisterBibs</a></span> <span class="odate time_1317970725 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">07 Oct 2011 06:58</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1275792">
									

<p>Long and short of this one? I had read <a href="/clef101">Clef's Guide To Reality Warpers</a>, and was writing one about training / briefing Agents. Then <a href="/orientation">Orientation</a> was written, and rather than throw away the work, I decided to write it a primer for Agents who do initial intelligence and appraisal of items. My goal of the piece was to treat Intel Agents somewhat as know-it-alls, because knowing stuff is their job.</p>
<p>I'm not 100% sure if the title is appropriate, but it came out of an unintended accident. I tend to write like I talk, and when I was going over the piece I realized that I was writing the word &quot;shit&quot; to cover things like intelligence, recon, etc. Rather than change a few of them, I decided to keep them in, mentally fanwank that Character-Bibs uses the term as a vague &quot;important information&quot; word, and labelled the page accordingly.</p>

							</div>

								
					
